                  <history>
                     <origin>
                        <origDate from="1600" to="1820"> </origDate>
                        <p>All names following the phrase <foreign xml:lang="gez">ገብርከ፡</foreign>
                           ‘your servant’ in the supplication formulas throughout the manuscript are
                           erased. Several layers of erasures and replacements are evident in the
                           supplication formulas. The name <foreign xml:lang="gez">ዮሐንስ፡</foreign>,
                           once itself crudely written over erasure, is still legible here and there
                           (e.g. <locus target="#23rb #45ra"/>). <persName
                              ref="PRS13180GabraSellase" role="scribe"/> is mentioned as the scribe
                           of <ref target="#a2"/>.</p>
                        <p>The mention of King ʾIyoʾas, that can refer either to <persName
                              ref="PRS5636IyoasI"/> (r. 1755–1769) or <persName ref="PRS5637IyoasI"
                           /> (r. 1818–1821), serves as a <foreign xml:lang="la">terminus ante
                              quem</foreign> for the production of <ref target="#p2"/>. The earliest
                           possible date of production – taken the handwriting of the main text and
                           codicological aspects into account – can be set to the seventeenth
                           century.</p>
                     </origin>
                     <provenance>The manuscript originates from Eritrea according to <bibl>
                           <ptr target="bm:Zanutto1932Bibliografia"/>
                           <citedRange unit="page">92</citedRange>
                        </bibl>). </provenance>
                  </history>
